OL,5,CThe ONE SHOW      F                    
OL,6,FThe magazine-style show tackles current
OL,7,Faffairs and other issues in the UK     
OL,8,Fusing a mix of interviews, topical     
OL,9,Fstories and features. Regular          
OL,10,Fcontributors offer reports relating to 
OL,11,Fsuch subjects as history, wildlife,    
OL,12,Fconsumer affairs, and health and       
OL,13,Fmedicine.

OL,5,CThe ONE SHOW                           
OL,6, What was teletext? It was an electronic
OL,7, magazine hidden in the TV signal that  
OL,8, could be viewed using any TV that had  
OL,9, a decoder. It delivered news, sport,   
OL,10, weather, TV and radio schedules. The   
OL,11, commercial channels also sold holidays 
OL,12, and other services. In the era before  
OL,13, the internet it was the fastest way to 
OL,14, get information.                       
OL,16,FUsing the technology of the 1970s it   
OL,17,Fwas limited to 24 rows of 40 characters
OL,18,For blocky graphics and seven colours.  
OL,20,FThis meant that stories were stripped  
OL,21,Fto the essentials and perfect for      
OL,22,Fstaying up to date on the news.

OL,6,FTeletext also had its own soap called  
OL,7,FPark Avenue, and comics such as Turner 
OL,8,Fthe Worm and the Adventures of 4-T.    
OL,10, Also fondly remembered is Digitiser    
OL,11, which was avidly read by fans of video 
OL,12, games. It was a magazine that included 
OL,13, reviews, fake adverts and a huge array 
OL,14, of surreal characters.                 
OL,16, Teefax has a couple of examples but    
OL,17, Turner the Worm couldn't come because  
OL,18, he was sick.

OL,5,CSO WHAT'S THIS ALL ABOUT?              
OL,6,FI'm reviewing the last track on every  
OL,7,Falbum in the NOW That's What I Call    
OL,8,FMusic! series.                         
OL,9,B                                       
OL,10,CFOR CRYING OUT LOUD, WHY?              
OL,11,FIn an age of instant playlists and     
OL,12,FSpotify, you might think the           
OL,13,Fcompilation album dead, but they're    
OL,14,Fresilient things - cropping up in      
OL,15,Fsupermarkets, petrol stations and even 
OL,16,Frecord shops. Why not, then, strike a  
OL,17,Fblow for curation and look at the      
OL,18,Fgrandaddy of them all? NOW compilations
OL,19,Fstill pack a cultural punch, out-      
OL,20,Fselling most other albums each year.   
OL,21,FSo what about the art of creating them?
OL,23,D]C        NOW reviews: p421            
OL,24,ANOW reviews BNew Digi!C EventsF Archive

OL,3,R`````````ba````````````````````````````
OL,4,                                     2/2
OL,5,CSO YOU'RE REVIEWING... THEELASTCTRACK? 
OL,6,FThat's it. See, it's not difficult to  
OL,7,Fstart a compilation. You need something
OL,8,Fbig, bombastic, ideally a recent Number
OL,9,F1. Probably Queen, to be honest. But   
OL,10,Ffinishing it? Hmm. Do you go for a pop 
OL,11,Fgem? Opt for classic rock? Or maybe,   
OL,12,Fgiven there's nothing to lose at this  
OL,13,Fstage, an experimental or novelty hit? 
OL,14,FAs we'll see, NOW goes for them all in 
OL,15,Fturn, which makes the last tracks on   
OL,16,Fthe albums far more fascinating and    
OL,17,Fvaried than the first ones.            
OL,18,F                                       
OL,19,FSo let's skip to the end and see what  
OL,20,FNOW has to offer the diligent. Hold on 
OL,21,Fto your headphones...                  
OL,22,F                                       
OL,23,D]C        NOW reviews: p421

OL,5,ENOW 1: CULTURE CLUB - VICTIMS          
OL,6,EPeaked atFNumber 3Ein December 1983    
OL,8,GIt was the occult fireside companion,  
OL,9,GPrediction magazine, that looked at Boy
OL,10,GGeorge's birth star chart in 1984 and  
OL,11,Gforesaw he would soon stop collecting  
OL,12,Gdolls, settle down and get a nice wife.
OL,14,FHindsight, unlike astrology, is an     
OL,15,Fexact science, but in spite of his     
OL,16,Finterview with Woman magazine where he 
OL,17,Fprofessed relationships with men and   
OL,18,Fwomen, few outside Culture Club would  
OL,19,Fhave known about George O'Dowd's       
OL,20,Fultimately troubled relationship with  
OL,21,Fthe band's drummer, Jon Moss.          
OL,22,F                                   1/4

OL,5,ENOW 1: CULTURE CLUB - VICTIMS          
OL,7,FBut that relationship turned out to be 
OL,8,Fthe dynamo behind many of Culture      
OL,9,FClub's early hits, and this is probably
OL,10,Fthe tensest of those. Now 1's already  
OL,11,Ftreated us to Karma Chameleon (side two
OL,12,Ftrack one), but the compilation's      
OL,13,Fcloser couldn't be more different.     
OL,14,F                                       
OL,15,FSparse and unsparing, Victims majors on
OL,16,Fsolo piano and strips back the layers  
OL,17,Fto bare emotional bruising. Culture    
OL,18,FClub were always good at this - Karma  
OL,19,FChameleon is one of the most upbeat    
OL,20,Fsongs about alienation you'll ever     
OL,21,Fhear.                                  
OL,22,F                                   2/4

OL,5,ENOW 1: CULTURE CLUB - VICTIMS          
OL,6,E                                       
OL,7,FVictims, though, doesn't sugar-coat its
OL,8,Fbleakness - it pulls back the mask and 
OL,9,Fwhat's revealed is red-raw.            
OL,10,G                                       
OL,11,FSo it's powerful melodically, and the  
OL,12,Flyrics? Ah... not so much. They're     
OL,13,Foddly throwaway, George sings of 'those
OL,14,Fthings' repeatedly, and it's as if the 
OL,15,Fband had 'Finish words to Victims' on a
OL,16,Fto-do list but didn't quite manage to  
OL,17,Fget round to it before release. Culture
OL,18,FClub's strength in verbal, as well as  
OL,19,Fvocal, hooks isn't really in evidence  
OL,20,Fhere, and this smacks of a disposable  
OL,21,Falbum track rather than a Top 3 single.
OL,22,F                                   3/4

OL,5,ENOW 1: CULTURE CLUB - VICTIMS          
OL,6,E                                       
OL,7,FVictims is also an odd, and possibly   
OL,8,Fdefining, choice for a Now closing     
OL,9,Ftrack. Not the obvious smoochy school- 
OL,10,Fdisco finale you might expect, it's a  
OL,11,Fdeal more challenging than that.       
OL,12,FBut it's still an oddly unambitious    
OL,13,Fway to finish the first in a           
OL,14,Fcompilation series that certainly      
OL,15,Fhasn't lacked ambition over the years. 
OL,16,FWe've got at least 104 more episodes to
OL,17,Fgo in that story.                      
OL,18,F                                       
OL,19,CWith thanks to Howard Ingham           
OL,20,F                                       
OL,21,F                                       
OL,22,F                                   4/4
